solutions.content:
lets take 10 as an example.
First thing came up to my mind was that the problem can break down as 
```
int result = Math.max(2 * integerBreak(10 - 2) * i, 3 * integerBreak(10 - 3), 4 * integerBreak(10 - 4)...)
```

So we have our solution as,
```
public int integerBreak(int n) {
	if (n <= 2) return 1;//base case
	int solution = 0;
	for(int i = 2; i<n; i++) {
		solution = Math.max(solution, i * integerBreak(n-i));
	}
	return solution;
}
```

However, after plug a couple number in, we will soon find out that our answer is wrong.
For example, plug in 4 would yield `2 * integerBreak(4-2)` which leads to `2 * 1 = 3`, because our base case is `if (n <= 2) return 1;` which is correct if the input is 2, but not if it is greater than 2. 

So, we have a corner case to take care.

After some experiment, it's not hard to see that when n <=4, n always bigger than break down product. Hence, our algorithm could be improved as follow.
```
public int integerBreak(int n) {
	if (n <= 2) return 1;//base case
	int solution = 0;
	for(int i = 2; i<n; i++) {
		if(n-i <= 4) solution = Math.max(solution, i * (n-i));//the corner discussed above
		else solution = Math.max(solution, i * integerBreak(n-i));
	}
	return solution;
}
```

Last step, it is not hard to see that we have repeated calculation that could be cached.
```
public int integerBreak(int n) {
	return integerBreak(n, new int[n+1]);
}

public int integerBreak(int n, int[] cache) {
	if (n == 2) return 1;
	if(cache[n] > 0) return cache[n];//we have calculated the result before, so return it
	int solution = 0;
	for(int i = 2; i<n; i++) {
		if(n-i<=4) {
			solution = Math.max(solution, i * (n-i));
		}else {
			solution = Math.max(solution, i * integerBreak(n - i, cache));
		}
	}
	cache[n] = solution;//cache the result
	return solution;
}
```

