# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The problem is to break a given integer n into the sum of at least two positive integers and maximize the product of those integers.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
The approach used here is dynamic programming. The idea is to maintain an array dp where dp[i] represents the maximum product that can be obtained by breaking the number i into at least two positive integers.

To compute dp[i], we iterate over all possible ways of breaking i into two positive integers j and i-j, and calculate the product of dp[j] and dp[i-j]. We take the maximum of this product and dp[i] to update dp[i].

The final answer is dp[n].

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
The outer loop iterates n-1 times, and the inner loop iterates i times for each iteration of the outer loop. Therefore, the time complexity is O(n^2).

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
We use an array dp of size n+1. Therefore, the space complexity is O(n).

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int integerBreak(int n) {
        int[] dp = new int[n+1];
        for(int i=1; i<n; i++)
        {
            for(int j=1; j<i+1; j++)
            {
                if(i+j<=n)
                {
                    dp[i+j]=Math.max(Math.max(dp[i],i)*Math.max(dp[j],j), dp[i+j]);
                }
            }
        }
        return dp[n];
    }
}
```

