**Approach:-**

In dp helper function i have taken three arguments n, dp array and m
In each recursive call we will try with the product of all possible number from 1 to n and check at which case we get maximum answer.
After that if n!=m (m is the original number itself) then n itself may be the possible maximum product, so we have checked the max(ans,n) only when n is not equal to the original input number. 
Kindly have a look into the code below for better understanding

**Complexity:-**
**Time :-** O(n^2)
**Space :-** O(n)

**Code:-**
```
class Solution {
    int helper(int n,vector<int> &dp,int m){
        if(n==1){
            return dp[n] = 1;
        }
        if(dp[n]!=-1){
            return dp[n];
        }
        int ans = 1;
        for(int i=1;i<=n;i++){
            if(n-i>0){
                ans = max(ans,(i*helper(n-i,dp,m)));
            }
        }
        if(n!=m){
            ans = max(ans,n);
        }
        return dp[n]=ans;
    }
public:
    int integerBreak(int n) {
        vector<int> dp(n+1,-1);
        return helper(n,dp,n);
    }
};
```

