The main idea is --  **break it into 3 as many as possible**.
if  4 --> 2 x 2. (They are the same no matter u break it or not)
if  5 --> 2 x 3
if 6  --> 3 x 3 
if 7 --> 3 x 4   (because 3 * 3 * 1 is useless, just take 3 * 4)
if 8 --> 3 x 3 x 2

So numbers greater than 3 should be breakdown

```
class Solution:
    def integerBreak(self, n: int) -> int:
        if n == 2 or n == 3:
            return n - 1                # must break into 1 & (n-1)

        num_3 = n // 3                  # break the number into (3+3+3+...) + remainder

        if n%3 == 0:                    
            return 3**num_3             # (3+3+3+...)
        if n%3 == 2:
            return (3**num_3) * 2       # (3+3+3+...) + 2     
        if n%3 == 1:
            return 3**(num_3-1) * 4     # (3+3+3+...) + 1 --> (3+3+...) + 3 + 1 -- > (3+3+...) + 4

