solutions.content:
**Basic Intution** : maximum product  can be achieved in two cases 
								1) for each i till n we calculate i *(n-i) and take max of it
								2)  for each i till n we calculate i* recursion of (n-i)  and take max of it. 
We use dp to store repetitive subproblems
	dp[i] represents max product we can achieve breaking the sum i
	Note: it necessarily doesn't need to i*subproblem(n-i) for ans to be max the answer can be maximum in cases where i*(n-1)
	Eg: 5
		Case1: n=5 i=2
			3+2=5 
			3x2=6
		Case 2: n=5 i=2
			2*memo(3,dp)=2*2=4;
		ans=max(case1,case2);
```
class Solution {
    public int memo(int n,int[] dp){
        if(dp[n]!=-1){
            return dp[n];
        }
        int max=0;
        for(int i=1;i<n;i++){
            max=Math.max(max,Math.max(i*(n-i),i*memo(n-i,dp)));
        }
        return dp[n]=max;
    }
    public int integerBreak(int n) {
        int dp[]=new int[n+1];
        Arrays.fill(dp,-1);
        dp[0]=0;
        dp[1]=1;
        memo(n,dp);
            // System.out.print(dp[i]+" ");
        return dp[n];
    }
}
