solutions.content:
It is similar to rod cutting problem or we can say unbounded knapsack problem subset.

in rod cutting problem we have price array which we want to maximize.
length n which is the total capacity.
and cutting can be done from 1 to n

Here two variables a and i can be used which will be initially set to n. where 'i' will serve as index and 'a' will serve as value which needed to be break.

instead of sum of prices which we want to maximize in rod cutting. here we want product of number to be maximum. hence we multiply it by i.

and on reaching range i.e. 0. instead of returning 0 we will return 1.(bcz multiplication by 0 make everything 0)

rod cutting example can be referenced on gfg site.

Note-> since in question it is mentioned that k>=2. we need to handle special check where n==3 or n==2 in such case answer will be 2 and 1. as if we did not apply this check. then by classic rod problem output of n=3 will be 3.

# Brute Force
```
public int integerBreak(int n) {
    return n<4?n-1:helper(n,n);
}
private int helper(int a,int i) {
    if(i==0 || a==0) {
        return 1;
    }
    if(a<i) {
        return helper(a,i-1);
    }
    return Math.max(helper(a,i-1),helper(a-i,i)*(i));
}
```

# Top Down DP
```
public int integerBreak(int n) {
    return n<=3?n-1:helper(n,n,new Integer[n+1][n+1]);
}
private int helper(int a,int i,Integer[][] memo) {
    if(i==0 || a==0) {
        return 1;
    }
    if(memo[a][i]!=null) {
        return memo[a][i];
    }
    if(a<i) {
        return memo[a][i]=helper(a,i-1,memo);
    }
    return memo[a][i]=Math.max(helper(a,i-1,memo),helper(a-i,i,memo)*(i));
}
```
# Bottom Up DP
```
public int integerBreak(int n) {
    if(n<4) {
        return n-1;
    }
    int[][] memo=new int[n+1][n+1];
    for(int i=0;i<=n;i++) {
        for(int a=0;a<=n;a++) {
            if(i==0||a==0) {
                memo[a][i]=1;
            }
            else if(a<i) {
                memo[a][i]=memo[a][i-1];
            } else {
                memo[a][i]=Math.max(memo[a][i-1],memo[a-i][i]*i);
            }
        }
    }
    return memo[n][n];
}
